segments.text: What about some highlights or some insights, observations, or something that stands out as biggies during your time here?
One thing that would stand out would be in the mid-70s.
We, Teacher Education in Texas, have been operating under the 1955 English for Teachers certification.
It's in 55.
It works with no change.
Well, it's a modification.
But basically, the standards have been in place.
During the early 1970s, we went through this competency-based JABS and different kinds of things.
And there was a lot of disagreement in the state between the among institutions and so forth.
and they couldn't agree upon a set of standards.
And actually, it got to the point where they said, okay, institution, you can choose from 75 standards or, I think, 74 standards or whatever.
Well, shortly after that, we went through our accreditation period with UVA.
Since the early 70s, like about 72, we had half a semester required.
The 1955 standards said
had to be a minimum of six hours.
That is, a half a day all semester or all day for half a semester.
Well, ours has been virtually twice that.
The GEA comes in and tells us that we won't be accredited because our student keeps, you know, blew us away.
So we chose to go to the mat.
And of course, if we don't meet the minimums, where do you come off telling us?
Well, the TEA's interpretation of that was that the attorney general said that you must have a minimum program.
And so there was a whole series of letters that went back and forth from Dean Hubert to Commissioner Edgar and other parties.
And finally, my perception is that TDA, rather than put themselves up for encouraging minimum standards, plus rather than fight Texas A&M, they just chose to ignore it.
And so the next time that they came for a accreditation visit, they didn't even look at that.
So they didn't have to write up .
Now, as an aside, there's no question that Dr. Huber's personal relationship with J.W.
Edgar, I'll try to write that up, but J.W.
Edgar and Dean Huber went back 100 years.
So that was Alton Bowen.
Alton Bowen became Commissioner of Education after J.W.
Edgar.
Well, as it so happened, Alton Bowen went to the Commissioner's office
the superintendency at the Mahea schools.
Prior to Mahea, he had been the superintendent.
No, he went from there.
Anyway, early on, early 70s, Alton Boyd was superintendent of the schools for Brian.
You know, the cronies in public education during the 60s and the 70s, in the real behind-the-scenes movers and shakers,
You look at .
And then you had another guy over at UT who, early on in the 50s and 60s, was Professor of UT.
OK, now one of the things that I haven't touched on, I keep forgetting to ask some of the people, but two or three have mentioned it, is the role of the development council.
And I know you work very, very closely with the council in establishing some of the programs.

you know, that you feel, you know, was the, and again, you know, forgetting the development council, but the way that, well, I'm not saying this is your honor, but really, has that had any kind of an impact on the?
Oh, absolutely.
Okay.
Absolutely.
If you look at six years ago in college of education, we virtually had no funding for scholarships at the undergraduate level.
Okay.
that were dollars controlled by the College of Education.
Our kids could compete at the university level with university-wide scholarships, but we had no undergraduate dollars available.
Just in those six short years, primarily through the Development Council, we have over a million dollars that are available to kids in scholarships now, directly to College of Education kids.
To me, and obviously, since I focus on undergraduate efforts, that has been a major accomplishment that we could not have done without the .
It's Friday the 13th.
Do you have a crystal ball that might tell you where you're going to be on Friday the 13th of the 21st century sometime?
Where do you see the future for this college at this point from where you're sitting?
I think that depends on where education is in the state.
I see some major, I see the potential for a major conflict between policy makers at the state level, here I'm talking about the state board, the coordinating board,

potential legislators, major potential conflict between perception of what is and what is not right with education and old and other profession in meeting those needs, how those perceived needs should be addressed.
The realization of education really bothers me because

We could very easily, in fact, we're almost at that point, close to the point of, as a profession, losing any kind of control or input as to what, you know, I think a lot of it is based on education is one of our societal institutions that everybody has been through, everybody has experienced.
there is not only a tendency, but there is little effort to learn about or to acquire or to believe in the social science research and education research as a basis for policymaking.
This is because it's not
directly cause and effect kind of stuff.
And you cannot quantify it in such a way that lends itself to those kinds of things.
I think the ability or the lack or the willingness of the professional education community to get involved in
politics.
And I've got a theory on this, but that's outside what you're doing.
Well, I think I know what you're saying about it, too.

Kind of an apathetic type, you know, you can't do anything other than... Well, that, and I think teachers as a general rule, educators as a general rule, that if, and this is stereotypical, but I think educators as a general rule, one of the reasons that they go into education, because of their personality makeup as such,
that they're not the hard-driving, competitive, beat the other guy, win this business deal kind of folks.
They're more the socially-oriented, health, consciousness kind of thing.
And because of that, are not comfortable, whether they go through any kind of a program or any kind of experiential deal,

that makes them politically sensitive, they get into their classroom, which is a very isolated environment, and time marches by, and as early on, when maybe they still have a little bit of idealism or what have you, they'll buck the system a little bit or push on the issue or what have you, and they get slapped down.
They get slapped down from the administrators
because the administrators were in the same boat that they were before.
That's what happened to them.
They don't know how to deal with somebody who has got some new ideas or some creative things.
They want to line all these things up because whenever you increase a person's degrees of freedom, then that means your management task is more difficult.
See, what you want to do is control them.
You want to pack them in little boxes and keep them in those boxes.
And that is a reinforcing kind of thing because when you're dealing with kids, you have to do that because degrees of freedom have to be related to level of maturity.
And so while your teachers and your administrators are suffering from the environment in which they find themselves,
So none of this works together.
It works against teachers and administrators being politically active.
Is it as much in the higher education?
I mean, how high is it different between higher ed and the special ed?
The mindset's totally different.
Totally different.
Because in higher education, in a major institution like this, it has to be different.
In fact, you have to encourage creativity.
You have to encourage differences.

And I have seen a lot of people come and go, your folks who've been in business or military who those degrees of freedom and don't know how to manage action of individual faculty who have their own agenda and who should have their own agenda.
But how do you get the department to move collectively in this direction when you've got all these folks doing all this?
It's a very delicate task.
But as soon as you change that assumption that my job as administrator is to line everybody up and march them down the road, you've lost it.
or department, or whatever, is on the decline.
Exactly.

And you can't do all of what a college or a university needs to do with all kinds of politics, because then you have no commonality of values to drive an institution.

in order to have some continuity, in order to pull things together.

Everybody's very reluctant to answer this question, but do you feel, I hope you're going to be here forever and ever, but if you ever leave here, what would you like to be remembered by?
What do you think has been your biggest contribution?
Everybody wants somebody else to talk about it, and people have it, and I have gotten it from different people.
I would like to think that there were a lot of, excuse me, Barbara.
Like who?
Barbara.
Oh, okay.

I could think I have a hand in helping the Baylor College of Medicine.
Drop by at graduation time or drop me a little note or come by.

That's why I think about teaching.
You never really see it.
That's why I'm here.
That's what I'd like to do.
There are kids out there that are more than they thought they could be because, you know, understanding their situations and didn't just shut them out.
Well, I thank you very, very much for your interview and a long time at the end of the day on Friday the 13th.
I really appreciate it, and I hope you'll let me come back.
